","1421–Female":"1421–Deceased","1460":"1460","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1459":"1459","1545":"1545","1544":"1544","about 1459":"about 1459","1421":"1421","1486":"1486","1530":"1530","1485":"1485","1518":"1518","after 1486":"after 1486","1549":"1549","1438":"1438","Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Nayland, Suffolk, England","Wiston, on, Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Nayland, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gerard","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Camille, Jean-Pierre, Murielle, Emile, Pascal, Pierre, Agathe, Alain, Aldes, Antoine, Armand.","French (<b>Gérard</b>), Walloon (mainly <b>Gérard</b>), and English (of Norman origin): from the personal name <i>Gérard</i>, <i>Gerard</i> (from Old French <i>Gerart</i>, <i>Girart</i>), composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. As a surname of French origin it is also found in Haiti. Compare   Garrard   and also French   Guerard  , English   Garard  ,   Gerrard  , and   Jarrard  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerardi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Vito, Enzo, Gaspare, Luigi, Rocco, Antonio, Canio, Carmine, Filippo, Francesco, Giovanni, Libero.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gerardo</i> (see   Gerard  ). This surname is also found in southern France.","German and French (mainly Nord): Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name German   Gerhard  , French <i>Gérard</i> (see   Gerard  ), using the genitive of the Latinized form <i>Gerardus</i>."]},{"name":"Garrison","meanings":["English: from a shortened form of Middle English <i>Gerardson</i>, a patronymic from the personal name   Gerard   + <i>son</i>, or an Anglicized form of its Dutch cognate   Gerritsen  . The English surname is probably in most cases of Flemish or Dutch origin. It was brought to Britain by immigrants from the Low Countries, especially in the 15th and 16th centuries.","Americanized form of Jewish   Gerson   (see   Gershon  ).","Americanized form of Dutch   Gerritsen  ."]},{"name":"Garrard","meanings":["English (London and East Anglia): variant of   Gerard  .","Altered form of French <b>Gérard</b> (see   Gerard  ).","History: This surname (see 2 above) is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of South Carolina."]},{"name":"Geenen","meanings":["Dutch, Flemish, and North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Geen</i>, a pet form of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Gerardo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Francisco, Alberto, Alfredo, Aurelio, Carlos, Jesus, Juan, Norberto, Ramon, Tomas, Ana.  Italian Antonio, Carmine, Dino, Enrico, Marco, Marco Antonio.","Spanish and Italian: from the personal name <i>Gerardo</i> (see   Gerard  )."]},{"name":"Gerald","meanings":["English (of Norman origin); French (<b>Gérald</b>): from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Gerald</i>, <i>Girald</i>, composed of the elements <i>gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’ and <i>wald</i> ‘power, authority’. It was introduced to Britain by the Normans and was fairly common, but less so than   Gerard  , with which it was early confused. In France the much more common variants of this surname are <b>Géraud</b> and   Giraud  ."]},{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["English: variant of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Geron","meanings":["French (<b>Géron</b>): from the personal name <i>Gero</i>, <i>Gerone</i>, a short form of ancient Germanic names formed with the element <i>gār, gēr</i> ‘spear, lance’, as for example <i>Gérard</i> (see   Gerard  ).","Altered form of French <b>Guérin</b> (see   Guerin  ).","English (Lancashire): of Norman origin, from the personal name <i>Geron</i> of ancient Germanic origin, a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Gherardi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Silvio, Alessandro, Angelo, Antonio, Donato, Egidio, Ennio, Enzo, Gildo, Lucio, Luigi, Primo.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of <i>Gherardo</i>, one of themany Italian equivalents of   Gerard  ."]},{"name":"Garard","meanings":["English (London and Buckinghamshire): variant of   Gerard  ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":90,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":99,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705205,"age":110,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Eleanor Gerard was born about 1459, in England, her father, Thomas Gerard, was 23 and her mother, ducia dowsa Assheton, was 39. She had at least 2 sons with John Warren."},"et":{"about 1459–":"umbes 1459–Surnud","1459–Female":"1459–Surnud","1459–1518":"1459–1518","1460–1530":"1460–1530","1485–1544":"1485–1544","1485–1545":"1485–1545","1486–Female":"1486–Surnud","1438–Male":"1438–Surnud","1421–Female":"1421–Surnud","1460":"1460","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1459":"1459","1545":"1545","1544":"1544","about 1459":"umbes 1459","1421":"1421","1486":"1486","1530":"1530","1485":"1485","1518":"1518","after 1486":"pärast 1486","1549":"1549","1438":"1438","Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Nayland, Suffolk, England","Wiston, on, Nayland, Suffolk, England":"Nayland, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"about 1459–":"noin 1459–Kuollut","1459–Female":"1459–Kuollut","1459–1518":"1459–1518","1460–1530":"1460–1530","1485–1544":"1485–1544","1485–1545":"1485–1545","1486–Female":"1486–Kuollut","1438–Male":"1438–Kuollut","1421–Female":"1421–Kuollut","1460":"1460","1569":"1569